The corporate juggernaut
of the University of
Pittsburgh Medical Center is
continuing to create a net-
work of health care institu-
tions spanning western
Pennsylvania.

Wednesday, the UPMC
announced its plan to enter
into “formal merger discus-
sions” with Passavant
Hospital in the North Side.
For the UPMC, it is not an
altogether surprising
announcement, as the past
year has seen them form
mergers with several other
hospitals in the city and its
surrounding areas, including
South Side, Beaver, and
Braddock hospitals. The area
north of the city has been the
only region that hasn’t been
reached by their influence.

“What we’re doing is

establishing a presence in-

the North Hills,” said Jane
Duffield of the UPMC news

WEATHER

bureau. “Since it is a grow-
ing area, it is necessary for
us to make that presence
known.” A

Under the agreement,
Duffield said Passavant will
retain its entire staff and
board of trustees, but will
gain the benefit of expansion
through the UPMC’s vast
resources.

As far as the UPMC
making its presence known,
and using this presence for
leverage in future merger
negotiations, Duffield would
only say that “the UPMC
wants to build a network of
quality health care through-
out western Pennsylvania.
As you add quality institu-
tions, you can develop syn-
ergy.”

Ironically, while the
UPMC was in the process of
merging with other area hos-
pitals over the past year,
Passavant maintained its
stand as an independent hos-
pital in the midst of the
UPMC’s dealings.

However, remaining an
independent hospital was no
longer possible, according to
Passavant representative
Robyn Beckwith.

“The changing health
care environment has made
it necessary to evaluate our
future,” she said. “In today’s
heavily managed health care
market, no community hos-
pital can stand alone.”

But such competition
could mean serious trouble
for hospitals such as
Allegheny General, which
also operates in the North
Side and is Passavant’s chief
competitor.

The merger may result in
some extensive expansion at
Passavant that could make
Allegheny suffer in terms of
patient admission. Such
competition, according to
Beckwith, is not the main
point of the merger.

“The issue is whether we
can provide a high level of
service to the community,”
said Beckwith.

 

