Student Government Board mem-
ber David Teeters has more on his mind
than University politics.

Back this school year from study-
ing abroad, Teeters clearly remembers
his experience backpacking across 40
different countries with four Pitt pro-
fessors and 20 other Pitt students.

” Out of those 40 countries, Teeters
doesn’t know which is his favorite.

“Maybe China or Russia. The cul-
tures are sodifferent [from ours],” the
junior said.

When asked which
course he has liked the
most since coming to Pitt,
he says the study abroad
experience has been by far
the most enjoyable for
him.

“You don’t realize that
you learn,” he said. “It
was an invaluable experi-
ence.”

One such experience
that Teeters remembers
happened while in Turkey,
when he was able to wit-
ness a 5 a.m. Islamic call
to prayer.

“Most people don’t
get to see that kind of
thing,” he said.

Teeters is interested in
many things outside of
SGB and world travel. As
a neuroscience/politics
and philosophy double-
major in the University
Honors College, he has
been able to participate in
other life—enhancing activ-
ities as well.

As a new volunteer in
the operating room at
Presbyterian University Hospital,
Teeters has seen the most technical
aspects of surgery.

“It [surgery] is nothing like ‘ER.’
The doctors know what is going to hap-
pen ahead of time, so there isn’t all the
frenzy associated with an emergency
room,” he said.

Upon graduating, Teeters would
like to go into international health and
development as a career, combining
both the policy analysis and medical
aspects of his education.

This decision came to him while
studying abroad. His love of medicine
combined with his political knowledge
and background were two reasons
behind his pending career choice.

“The number of people I saw suf-
fering from basic health issues was
tremendous. They lack basic immu-
nizations,” he said.

 

“The saddest for me to see was
probably India, to see people die right
in front of you. But they don’t just die
that way. They have lived their whole
lives like that —— in filth.”

Back in America, Teeters is a
returning member of the University’s
crew team. He began rowing his fresh-
man year.

“At the first practice of my fresh-
man year, the coach said we were
going to go on a ‘ﬂat run.’ I naturally
thought ‘ﬂat’ meant ﬂat. It didn’t,” said
Teeters. Now though, Teeters really
misses those hills when he returns to
his hometown of
Cleveland, Ohio.

“Ohio and Pittsburgh
are really similar towns.
But Cleveland doesn’t
have those hills.”

Another activity
Teeters participates in here
at Pitt is teaching a reli-
gion course on Monday
evenings to sixth graders
from local public schools.

“They [the kids] call
me ‘Mr. Teeters’ and ask
me how many kids I
have,” he said, laughing.
“I even got Christmas pre-
sents this year. And I had
to schedule parent/teacher
conferences. I hated those
growing up. Now I am on
the other side,” he said.

Through teaching this
class, Teeters says that he
has gained much more
respect for teachers.

“It [the class] really
isn’t a religion course, per
se,” Teeters said. “I try to
be a role model to these
kids, more than teaching
them religion. Values are
taught less today, so these
kids need that.”

Through his travels, Teeters has
seen that other countries, whether they
be Islamic, Jewish, or Christian coun-
tries, have an important central system
of beliefs and teach those beliefs as a
way of life. “These beliefs might not
necessarily be religious, but they have
a set way of believing,” he said.

When he returned from his travels,
Teeters chose to live on-campus in the
dorms, mostly because, he says, he
couldn’t really choose off—campus
housing while he was away. I

“I’m looking forward to living off-
campus. But I like being on-campus
also. I came to college to experience it
all. I am in the middle of everything if
I live in the dorms,” he said.

At the pace Teeters is currently
moving, he should hit “the middle of
everything” pretty quickly.

