Under the silver dollar sun of
Corporate America, it’s a relief to
know that, amidst big bosses and

_ constant quests for quick capital,

there are a few who recognize the
labor behind the loot.

The ernployer/employee con-
nection has been less than stellar.
There’s a never-ending mind game
being played with both sides con-
fused about the rules. Bosses are
supposed to bark out orders and
obedient workers scarnper away in
fear, right? Or employers are
required to stand back and watch
employees mingle by the water
cooler taking advantage of the
employer’s kindness, right? Wrong.

There’s nothing wrong with
letting people know who’s the head
cheese. Obviously, boundaries must
be drawn between employers and
employees to stress that work
comes ﬁrst. But somewhere along
the line, the communication is hor-

ribly distorted, leaving mixed sig-
nals.

Some employers use their
positions like drugs, getting high off
power. I must admit, there is soure-

I thing about having the power to

makeorbreakalackeyonthespot.
But resorting to Mr. Spacely
“Jetson, yoouu’rree ﬁred!” tactics is
cruel.

Employers never realize the
gold mines they possess in their
employees. More employers need
to view jobholders as assets, not
expendable. There’s more to work
than hiring and ﬁring.

However, not all employers are
ogres in disguise. Many employees
have a habit of juicing employers
for their kindness. I’ve been in
many an ofﬁce and witnessed
employees huddled in dark comers,
in “I Hate My Boss” support
groups, exchanging ﬁivolous boss
frustrations like baseball cards.

“I can ’t believe she asked me to
call this, analyze that, type this,
check that  what does she expect
me to do, work?”

Some employees automatical-
ly expect their bosses to be
ruthless, overbearing, and intimi-
dating, which means the boss’ true
colors are never noticed.

So what can be done?

The main key is respect. In the
workplace, people need to respect
each other. Employers have to
remember two important things: 1.
that they were in the same position
at one point, and 2. most jobs suck
If given the choice, most people
wouldn’t be doing the mundane
routines they perform 365 days a
year. They’d be taking the boss’
place, making his money, and dri-
ving his car.

Employers also have to learn
how to show authority without
ﬂashing it in employees’ mugs.
They know who the boss is by the

signature on the paycheck

Employees, don’t take advan-
tage of a boss who’s given you
more than enough kindness. You
didn’t have to be hired, and there’s
always someone looking to wear
