Black to White, Brooklyn to Long
Island, the music of Jamaica bums like a
blunt in New York City. For almost a decade
and a half, that most unholy of words —
“ska” — has been a beacon of hope in an
often overrated New York music scene.
These, however, are the nineties, and the
American melting pot has turned into a vir-
tual car alarm, a ﬂagship of the postmodern
condition, and thus, the nineties have turned
to California — for CULTURE, of all
things! '

Tragic Kingdom is the massive unit-
mover from Californian ska—inﬂuenced pop-
sters No Doubt The very title refers to
Disneyland, refers to the Blade Runner
California that is so much more than a
movie. This is from whence the term “ska”
has entered the American vocabulary, and it
doesn’t need to be so, Rude Bwoy!

Invading the airwaves with pre-apoca-
lyptic, end-of—the-millenium ska, reggae,
and rocksteady are Brooklyn’s Insteps,
who’ve ﬁred on the Babylon that is the mod-
em ska scene with a salvo of revolution
ammunition. Come, my selector, come
now! Bring down the enemy with Eleven
Steps to Power, out on Another Planet
records, with the aid of legends of roots rebel
ska, Stubbom Records. Eleven Steps to
Power contains eleven tracks of music
steeped like Tea (and no Djarling, bay—bee)
in Jamaican popular music, without stagnat-
ing in the ska period like so many bands, or
bastardizing it into “—core” or “-punk” deriv-
atives.

The record begins with the call of leg-
endary Jamaican toaster King Stitt, and
kicks into “The Dragon,” a soul/go—go
experiment that shows olf the talented musi-
cians in the Insteps, especially drummer
Eddie Campo (sometimes loaned to label-

mate posse Stubborn All-Stars) and the
saxltrumpetltrombone , horn section.
Somehow, the track even holds in check the
guest appearance by King Stitt, who’s toast-
ing one would expect to overpower the
instrumentations.

From there on out, we’re treated to the
double vocals of Noah Roy and Peter
Loshak, who seem to have blended into one
style of phrasing and breathy, low—key soul-
singing. VV1th mad lyrics concerned with the
conditions under which we live in this mod-
em age, written, like all parts of the music.
with an eye on what has come before, it is
perhaps these Siamese vocals that are the
most lacking point in the record. There may
as well be one singer. The styles are so sim-
ilar, and at times the melodies can blur
together through the tracks. Still, songs like
“The Sufferer” and “Every Slacker Is A
Star” are on a level achieved in ska by few
bands —— Insteps buddies Slackers and
Skinnerbox being among that elite.

“I will pour the gasoline/Down on the
hotter ﬁre/Witness the hour the wicked
lease/on Earth shall expire/Brimstone talkin’
prophet squawking/Fussin’, Moanin’,
Bitchin’/If you can’t stand the heat broth-
er/You best get out the kitchen.” Heavy
words, written under heavy manners. The
Insteps get points for Reggae-esque
Revelations in their revolutions, and for
mighty music grafted onto the unsuspecting
public by their organ/soulero guitar/drop
bass/drums/horns/vox lineup. If you’re
expecting to hear four guys with new distor-
tion pedals expound the virtues of skinhead
girls and cheap beer, look elsewhere; if you
want a little irie with your ska, take the Steps.

Check out the Insteps live tonight with
D.C’.s Eastern Standard Time and locals
the B-3 ’s and the Sussed at Charlies Bistro,
Forbes Ave, across ﬁvm Palumbo Center
7:30 pm, All Ages. Riddim Rielin ’!

