The new Blonde Redhead seven-inch
is pretty. It looks like my grandma’s liv-
ing room with the puke green couch,

golden recliner, and rust orange curtains. .

You know what I’m, talking about. If it
had those furry, round, frilly things bor-
dering the sleeve, it would make for a
ﬁne, sofa pillow. '

I have to admit, I was really worried
that songs would never be able to live up
to the brilliant quality suggested by the
packaging. Fortunately, I was wrong.

“Symphony of Treble” opens up with
just that. Meandering keyboards and
high-pitched feedback start the chaos.
Soon, the keyboard is replaced by a
whimpering trumpet backed by a tight
rhythm section that holds it all together.
Supported by calmly staggering vocals
by the guy (I’ll probably get his name
wrong because I always confuse the
vocalists. You decide: either Amedeo or
Kazu), this song can do no wrong.

The B—side is much the same but with
one advantage — super—sweet vocals by
the other singer (again, your pick). For
those of you who aren’t already aware,
the sounds emanating from her mouth are
those of an angel, albeit one in a bit of
pain. Soft, cuddly words of a six-year—old
slowly transform into sustained screeches
that could shatter windows at full force.
This sounds sexy in a way one seldom
imagines something “sexy” would sound.

The record follows the band’s second
LP La Mia Wta Wolenta on the Smells
Like Records label. It is deﬁnitely worth
having, along with their first on the same
label, if you like Sonic Youth and the
vocals described above. For those who
care, the seven—inch was produced by
Guy Picciotto from Fugazi and is the first

release for Touch and Go. If you already.

dig them, you will definitely dig this, as it

takes their sound one step further in an

undoubtedly positive direction.
—bretferree

