The Rebirth of Cool Four
4th & B’way

It’s hip to like acid jazz.

At least that’s the word around town.
Just look around, and you will see “acid
jazz nights” popping up at clubs every-
where.

It’s the newest craze in music ... only
it isn’t new. Acid jazz has only come into
vogue recently with promotion by big
name labels for groups like US3, Massive
Attack, and Portishead.

Even more well known rap acts, such
as A Tribe Called Quest, the Beastie
Boys, and the Jungle Brothers, have
helped promote acid jazz by experiment-
ing with different types of beats and
styles —— melding other genres with their

 

   

 

own. In fact, these groups have all made
appearances on the Rebirth of Cool
series.

With the fourth edition of the Rebirth
of Cool series, it is clear that acid jazz has
been around for a while and even clearer
that it isn’t going anywhere.

The proof of this can be found in the
fact that even in four years, the music of
the Rebirth of Cool series has evolved.
Not to say that the other three were infe-
rior; volume four just speaks wonders
about the creativity that drives the artists
behind the acid jazz scene.

Of course, the term “acid jazz” is
much like “altemative” in that it doesn’t
really exemplify the music it names.
“Altemative” used to be just that — an
alternative to the mainstream. Now it is
mainstream. Likewise, “acid jazz” came
from the melding of acid house beats and
jazz instrumentation. Now it stands for a
perplexing mix of several different gen-
res.

Take the first track of the album,
“Underwater Love” by Smoke City. It’s
far from jazz, lying somewhere between
ambient, the “James Bond” theme, and
Portishead. It starts the album out with an
overall feeling of sensuality that inches its
way into most of the tracks.

While a more traditional hip-hop
sound seemed to rule most of Volume
three, and volume two took on a jazzy
feel, this new version takes a look at the
ambient beats. Only, this is not ambient
music — each artist puts his own twist on
the genre, giving it the exotic mix that has
become familiar to acid jazz fans.

Still, like the previous three volumes,
there are definite hits and misses, though
there are more hits than misses. “Claire,”
by iO continues the feel, providing a
groovy little tune with a pinch of ambient
noise. It is probably the best track on the
album.

The most unusual, however, is the
effort by Outside, dubbed “To Forgive
But Not To Forget.” It melds techno
house beats with a soothing violin solo.
Think of it as a Russian orchestral version
of the latest Prodigy tune.

Not to be outdone, De Lata gives an
interesting mix of Latin and techno beats
with the song “Pontelo.” Only Lewis
Taylor’s “Bittersweet” truly disappoints.
After a great start, it slowly devolves into
a sickening mix of guitar—happy riffs and
bad R&B vocals.

There is little of what you would con-
sider “jazz” on the latest Rebirth of Cool
volume. Akasha’s “Jazz Garage” proba-
bly comes the closest, yet it still uses a
ﬂute over more traditional horns.

Overall, the album still remains fair-
ly close to its roots. While it may not
sound like traditional acid jazz, it is obvi-
ous that each track shares a common base
and expands on it. It is a wonderful con-
tinuation of an excellent series —— one
that mirrors the continual growth of the

music.
-——michaelfriedman

