The Heiress ,
Playhouse Theatre Company
directed Larry John Meyers

Henry James wrote down bits and
pieces of late-night gossip in 1879 about
love and its entanglements, and then pro-
ceeded to produce a novel out of that gossip
entitled “Washington Square.” Suffice it to
say that the novel remained in relative
obscurity until Ruth and Augustus Goetz
decided to make it into a play and call it
"Ihe Heiress.” Fortrmately for the Goetzes,
“The Heiress,” a story about midwinter love

and all that follows, successfully ran on .
Broadway and encouraged a movie version _

which won 4 Oscars in 1949. Recently,
“The Heiress” was revived on Broadway
and won a 1995 Tony Award for Best Play
and featured a wonderful Cherry Jones in
the lead role of Catherine Sloper.

. The Playhouse Theatre Company at
Point Park College is currently staging “The
Heiress” under the direction of stalwart

Point Park—er Larry John Meyers. Meyers.

was “interested in the complex relationships
that occur in the novel and how [he] could
bring that to this production.” The story
revolves around a dominating and success-
ful Dr. Austin Sloper(John Amplas) and his
beautiful but timid daughter, Catherine
S1oper(Marie Elena O’Brien). Dr. Sloper is
interminably resentful of Catherine’s birth
(which caused the death of his wife) and is
conspicuously abusive towards her. Though
she is a captivating and prepossessing
young woman, she can do nothing to please
her father. Catherine’s aunt, Lavinia
Penniman(Sheila McKem1a), steps into the
scene and tries to encourage Catherine to
break out of her shell when she meets a
charming man named Morris

iTownsend(Brett Kennedy). Catherine,

being foolish and young, is immediately
smitten by Morris. Since Catherine is an
heir to her mother’s fortune, however, Dr.
Sloper thinks that perhaps Morris is only
after Catherine’s fortune — how very excit-
ing!

The story does get a bit non—soporiﬁc
near the end of the show when the charac-
ters break out of their Victorian molds and
shapes and start doin’ the Macarena! Just
kiddin’. In all seriousness, the story does
pick up momentum and displays a rare (for
the 18005) sensitivity for women’s expecta-

Thursday, January 30 ‘I997

 

tions and roles. The lead role of Catherine is
written with thoughtfulness, albeit in a
somewhat limited fashion, and the Goetzes
account for her condition and her person
without thoroughly conforming to what a
Victorian woman should be. Catherine goes
through some rather intense positive
changes. This is indicative of her strength,
something women are rarely seen as pos-
sessing in this historical period. '
— Although I previewed this show rather
excitedly, I must admit that perhaps the text
isn’t strong enough to uphold the kind of
overall intensity that I was expecting. The
intensity of performance was certainly up to
the standard that I have come to expect from
all Craft Ave.-related theatre events, but the
text itself is, for lack of a better term, stale. I
maintain that the show achieves some rather
bold statements concerning women, but the
writing itself is simply not as thoughtful as
one would expect. Catherine falls in love
with the ﬁrst man she has the gumption to
talk to, and I have a hard time believing that
a woman experiencing her turmoil is that
simple. Regardless of my feelings on the
Goetzes’ writing, I applaud the overall work
of the show. Marie O’Brien, as Catherine,
displays a rather mature presence on stage
and seems quite comfortable within her
leading status. Brett Kennedy as “loverboy”
Morris has a rather striking Alec Baldwin
quality about him, and I am almost ashamed
to say that I liked it. He created a pretty
believable kind-of-too-passionate-
boyfriend—guy character but sometimes
when he smiled he was just a bit too hand-
some. Sheila McKemra and John Amplas,
as Aunt Lavinia and Dr. Sloper, respective-
ly, were respectable; Amplas, especially,
was so “there” that he was almost scary.
Hopefully, readers won’t be swayed by
my liking the statement of the show, hating
the text, and liking the acting. Is that even
possible? At a school as dedicated to quali-
ty as Point Park, it certainly is possible to
deal with all the aforementioned crap and
still come out on top with a good show.
“The Heiress” is playing at Playhouse
Theatre of Point Park College, 222 Craft
Ave, Wed. thru Sun., at 8 p.m. along with a
Sunday matinee. Fri. and Sat. shows $18
and all others $16. Students can purchase
rush tickets ( half price ) half an hour before
showtime. Call 621-4445.
I ——neil bose

      

