And, of course, since Lucas has a sense
of the dramatic, the special editions are being
released in 1997 to coincide with the 20th
anniversary celebration of the original release
of Star Wars —— and also to whip audiences
into a frenzy of anticipation for the upcoming
all—new Star Wars ﬁlms, which have been in
preproduction for well over a year and are
expected to hit theaters beginning in 1998.

Toward the millennium

Lucas has kept the speciﬁcs of the next
trilogy top secret, but the basics are no secret:
the new ﬁlms will chronologically precede
the original Star Wars (officially, Star Wars is
labelled as Episode Four, “A New Hope”),
and will tell the story of Luke Skywalker’s
father, Anakin. The ﬁrst movie will feature
the character of Obi—Wan Kenobi as a young
Jedi Knight, and will relate Kenobi’s first
meeting with the child, Anakin. The second
chapter will illustrate Kenobi’s training of

 

Anakin and their adventures together in the
Clone Wars. The conclusion will detail
Anakin’s fall to the forces of evil and eventu-
al transfonnation into Darth Vader.

No word on casting has come out yet,
but Lucas has tapped his Young Indiana
Jones collaborator Rick McCallum as pro-
ducer for the new series, and The Shawshank
Redemption scribe Frank Darabont as
screenwriter. Rumor has it that Lucas may
direct at least one of the ﬁlms himself; if true,
it would mark Lucas’ ﬁrst directorial venture
since the original Star Wars in 1977, the rig-
ors of which led him to abandon directing for
the less stressful position of story writer/exec-
utive producer. K

The ﬁnal question remains: can Lucas
do it again? His original vision capturedthe
imagination of the entire world; is it tempting
fate to try again? Or, worse, has the world
grown too accustomed to the cynicism of the
‘90s to appreciate Star Wars in the same way
it once did?

If history can be trusted, there’s hope.
After all, as many people read the Odyssey as
the Iliad. Apparently, not all sequels are
doomed to mediocrity.

—-stephen h. segal

